1 SECTION 3. ORS 418.201 is amended to read:
2 418.201. It is the intent of the Legislative Assembly that each foster child have certain essential
3 rights, including but not limited to the following:
4 (1) To have the ability to make oral and written complaints about care, placement or services
5 that are unsatisfactory or inappropriate, and to be provided with information about a formal process
6 for making complaints without fear of retaliation, harassment or punishment.
7 (2) To be notified of, and provided with transportation to, court hearings and reviews by local
8 citizen review boards pertaining to the foster child’s case. [when the matters to be considered or de-
9 cided upon at the hearings and reviews are appropriate for the foster child, taking into account the age
10 and developmental stage of the foster child.]
11 (3) To be provided with written contact information of specific individuals whom the foster child
12 may contact regarding complaints, concerns or violations of rights, that is updated as necessary and
13 kept current.
14 (4) To be protected from abuse, exploitation, neglect, intimidation, retaliation and
15 wrongful use of restraint or seclusion.
16 (5) To regularly attend school and to have access to a free and appropriate public edu-
17 cation.
18 (6) To be assigned an attorney to represent the foster child’s interests and to have un-
19 impeded and unmonitored contact with that attorney.
20 (7) To have unimpeded and unmonitored contact, as applicable, with the Residential Fa-
21 cilities Ombudsman, the Children’s Advocate or a foster care ombudsman who has been
22 formally designated by the Children’s Advocate or the Department of Human Services.
23 (8) To have an attorney or court-appointed advocate of the foster child’s choosing present
24 for any interview with law enforcement or abuse investigators, regardless of whether the
25 foster child is interviewed as a witness, a victim or a subject individual.
26 (9) To maintain and have access to personal belongings including but not limited to
27 clothing, books, toys, photographs and musical instruments.
28 (10) To be present at court hearings, including to be present at all court hearings re-
29 garding the child’s case.
30 (11) To transport belongings and personal effects in an appropriate luggage carrier when
31 entering into or transitioning or exiting from foster care.
32 [(4)] (12) When a foster child is 14 years of age or older, to be provided with written information
33 within 60 days of the date of any placement or any change in placement, regarding:
34 (a) How to establish a bank account in the foster child’s name as allowed under state law;
35 (b) How to acquire a driver license as allowed under state law;
36 (c) How to remain in foster care after reaching 18 years of age;
37 (d) The availability of a tuition and fee waiver for a current or former foster child under ORS
38 350.300;
39 (e) How to obtain a copy of the foster child’s credit report, if any;
40 (f) How to obtain medical, dental, vision, mental health services or other treatment, including
41 services and treatments available without parental consent under state law; and
42 (g) A transition toolkit, including a comprehensive transition plan.
43 [(5)] (13) With respect to a foster child’s rights under the federal and state constitutions, laws,
44 including case law, rules and regulations:
45 (a) To receive a document setting forth such rights that is age-appropriate and developmentally
