30 CHILDREN IN CARE
31
32 SECTION 5. ORS 409.185 is amended to read:
33 409.185. (1) The Director of Human Services shall oversee the development of standards and
34 procedures for assessment, investigation and enforcement of child protective services.
35 (2)(a) The Department of Human Services shall take action to implement the provision of child
36 protective services as outlined in ORS 417.705 to 417.800 and based on the recommendations in the
37 1992 “Oregon Child Protective Services Performance Study” published by the University of Southern
38 Maine.
39 (b) In all substantiated cases of child abuse and neglect, the role of the department is to com-
40 plete a comprehensive family assessment of risk of abuse or neglect, or both, assess service needs
41 and provide immediate protective services as necessary.
42 (c) The department shall provide remedial services needed to ensure the safety of the child.
43 (d) In all cases of child abuse and neglect for which a criminal investigation is conducted, the
44 role of law enforcement agencies is to provide a legally sound, child sensitive investigation of
45 whether abuse or neglect or both have occurred and to gather other evidence and perform other
[4]

A-Eng. SB 1533
1 responsibilities in accordance with interagency agreements.
2 (e) The department and law enforcement agencies shall conduct the investigation and assess-
3 ment concurrently, based upon the protocols and procedures of the county child abuse multidisci-
4 plinary team in each jurisdiction.
5 (f) When the department and law enforcement agencies conduct a joint investigation and as-
6 sessment, the activities of the department and agencies are to be clearly differentiated by the pro-
7 tocols of the county child abuse multidisciplinary team.
8 (g) Nothing in this subsection is intended to be inconsistent with ORS 418.702, 418.747 and
9 418.748 and ORS chapter 419B.
10 (h) In all cases of child abuse for which an investigation is conducted, the department shall
11 provide a child’s parent, guardian or caregiver with a clear written explanation of the investigation
12 process, the court hearing process and the rights of the parent, guardian or caregiver in the abuse
13 investigation and in the court proceedings related to the abuse investigation. When the depart-
14 ment provides the written explanation under this paragraph to a child’s parent or guardian,
15 the department shall include a disclosure that the representative of the department is acting
16 on behalf of the department and cannot provide legal advice to the parent or guardian.
17 (3) Upon receipt of a recommendation of the Children’s Advocate under ORS 417.815 (2)(e), the
18 department shall implement the recommendation or give the Children’s Advocate written notice of
19 an intent not to implement the recommendation.
